{"id": 231237874, "title": "95 Pet Dogs Were Bitten By Venomous Vipers\u2013Here\u2019s How Many Survived", "text": "Share to Facebook Share to Twitter Share to Linkedin New research explains what to do in the event that your pet is envenomated by a dangerous snake. getty A recent article published in Toxicon suggests that the survival rate for pet dogs that get bitten by deadly snakes is higher than might be expected. Of the 95 dogs analyzed in the study\u2013all of which had been bitten by extremely venomous pit vipers\u2013only five died. \u201cMost dogs will survive if treated promptly and appropriately with adequate amounts of intravenous fluids and antivenom titrated on severity of clinical presentation,\u201d state the authors of the research, led by Taylor Bassett of the University of Florida College of Veterinary Medicine. The research was conducted in northern Florida, where a variety of dangerous American pit vipers can be found, including the timber rattlesnake, water moccasin, eastern diamondback rattlesnake and dusky pygmy rattlesnake. Approximately 65% of North American venomous snakebites are caused by rattlesnakes. The deadly ... [+] timber rattlesnake, native to the eastern United States, is shown here. getty Pit vipers produce a dangerous venom cocktail, containing various combinations of hemotoxic, vasculotoxic, myotoxic and neurotoxic components. Envenomation can cause a wide range of symptoms such as tissue damage, blood clotting dysfunction, rapid heartbeat, and central nervous system dysfunction\u2013not to mention vomiting, diarrhea and organ damage. MORE FOR YOU Why Christina Ricci Is Giving Up Ownership Of Wednesday Addams WWE SmackDown Results, Winners And Grades On June 7, 2024 Howard University Returning Sean Diddy Combs 1 Million Donation Amid Sexual Misconduct Allegations The key to survival is getting your dog to a veterinary hospital or clinic as quickly as possible\u2013and making sure the appropriate amount of antivenom is administered. \u201cSometimes, the administered [antivenom] dose is limited because of cost constraints,\u201d report the researchers. \u201cIn some cases, the signs will initially decrease, only to later reappear because of dosage inadequacy and persistent or recurrent envenomation.\u201d The researchers note that a majority of envenomations documented in their research occurred during warmer months, between March and October. So, in the southeastern United States, pet owners should be aware of the heightened potential for snakebite during summer when snakes are most active. However, this trend may not be true in other areas of the country, so it\u2019s important for dog owners to assess and monitor the risks inherent to their local environments. Here are seven other tips for pet owners to mitigate the risk of snakebite for their animals and advice on what to do if your dog is bitten by a snake. Keep your yard clean and tidy. Snakes are attracted to cluttered areas where they can hide and hunt for prey. By maintaining a well-kept yard, you can reduce the chances of snakes setting up residence near your home. Regularly mow the lawn and remove piles of leaves, wood, and other debris. Supervise your dog during outdoor activities. When taking your dog for a walk or allowing them to play outside, always keep an eye on them. Avoid letting your dog wander off into tall grass, dense underbrush, or rocky areas where snakes are common. Stick to well-trodden paths and be vigilant during peak snake activity times, such as early morning and late evening. Educate yourself about local snake species. Knowing which venomous snakes are common in your area can help you take specific precautions. Familiarize yourself with the appearance and behavior of these snakes so you can identify them if encountered. Local wildlife agencies and veterinary clinics often provide resources and information on regional snake species. Enroll your dog in snake avoidance training. In regions were venomous snakes are particularly common, some trainers offer snake avoidance training for dogs. This training can teach your dog to recognize and avoid snakes, potentially preventing a dangerous encounter. Training methods typically involve using live (but safely restrained) snakes. Know the signs of a snakebite. Prompt identification and treatment of a snakebite can be lifesaving. Common signs of snakebite in dogs include severe swelling, bleeding puncture wounds, pain, lethargy, vomiting, diarrhea, and changes in breathing or behavior. At-home snakebite remedies are ineffective. At-home snakebite remedies are ineffective and can be harmful. Do not attempt treatments such as cutting, tourniquets, venom extraction, freezing, burning, shocking, or administering antihistamines or other medications unless recommended by a veterinarian. These methods have been scientifically proven to be ineffective and may cause further harm. Provide rapid veterinary care. If you suspect your dog has been bitten by a snake, seek veterinary care immediately. Antivenom is the only proven effective treatment for snakebite envenomation and must be administered at a veterinary clinic. The sooner antivenom is administered for a severe bite, the more effective it will be. After a snakebite, remove your dog's collar to prevent breathing difficulties if swelling occurs around the neck. If possible, take a photo of the snake to help with identification, which can aid in specific treatment options. However, do not attempt to kill or capture the snake, as this can lead to additional bites. Keep your dog as restricted and calm as possible and transport them to the nearest veterinary facility. Envenomation does not occur with every snakebite, and the veterinarian will monitor your dog to determine if antivenom is needed. In many cases, it won't be necessary. By taking these precautions and staying informed, you can significantly reduce the risk of snakebites and ensure your pet's safety and well-being. Scott Travers Following Editorial Standards Print Reprints & Permissions", "summary": "A recent article published in Toxicon suggests that the survival rate for pet dogs that get bitten by deadly snakes is higher than might be expected.", "url": "https://www.forbes.com/sites/scotttravers/2024/06/08/95-pet-dogs-were-bitten-by-venomous-vipersheres-how-many-survived/", "image": "https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/665605a48f94105d6b2cae6a/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&crop=1825,855,x0,y0,safe&height=900&width=1600&fit=bounds", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-06-08 13:13:12", "author": "Contributor,Scott Travers", "authors": ["Contributor", "Scott Travers"], "language": "en", "source_country": "US", "sentiment": -0.148}